const a = [
  {"id":5872,"text":"How is the immunity towards hepatitis B virus measured?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 873.","responses":[{"text":"Anti-HBeAb","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBcAg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBsAg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-HBcAb","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-HBsAb","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10382,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding split laceration?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 195.","responses":[{"text":"It looks like an incised wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can occur on the forehead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can occur on the scrotal skin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It occurs due to sudden compression between two hard objects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a type of laceration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10392,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a stab wound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200, 201.","responses":[{"text":"Its greatest dimension is depth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It results from piercing with a pointed weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a wedge shaped opening wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In this injury bruising around the opening of the wound is seen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It may occur with a knife","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10401,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding age and color of a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Normal at 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue on day 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow on day 7-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Depends on size and swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Green on day 2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12005,"text":"A patient with a duodenal ulcer comes to the clinic with a complaint of blood in vomiting. The ulcer has eroded the posterior wall of the duodenum and ruptured which artery?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 105. (2) Gastroduodenal Artery - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/gastroduodenal-artery. Accessed 20 Aug. 2022.","responses":[{"text":"Gastroduodenal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreaticoduodenal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12773,"text":"A 9-year-old child presents with a prolonged history of abdominal discomfort, bloating, constipation, weight loss, and anemia. Serological examination shows positivity for anti-endomysial antibodies. An endoscopic biopsy of the jejunum will most likely show which of the following features?","explanation":"The child's presentation is suggestive of celiac disease, an autoimmune condition triggered by ingestion of gluten in genetically predisposed individuals. The characteristic histological feature of celiac disease on jejunal biopsy is **villous atrophy**.\r\n\r\nPseudomembrane refers to a layer of exudate that can be found in conditions like pseudomembranous colitis, typically caused by *Clostridium difficile* infection. This is not associated with celiac disease.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Periodic Acid-Schiff (PAS) stain is used to detect polysaccharides such as glycogen and mucosubstances such as glycoproteins, glycolipids and mucins in tissues. This staining feature is associated with certain conditions like Whipple's disease, which causes a buildup of PAS-positive foamy macrophages in the small intestine. This is not seen in celiac disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 785.","responses":[{"text":"Villous expansion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomembrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PAS-postive granules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous atrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Loss of goblet cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13263,"text":"Which of the following is not related to an abrasion?","explanation":"**Abrasions** are superficial injuries that only involve the outermost layers of the skin. Due to their superficial nature, abrasions generally **do not leave permanent scars**, though they might leave temporary marks.\r\n\r\nRadiator grill refers to the patterned abrasion that can occur if someone is hit by a car and comes into contact with the front grille. The distinct pattern of the grille can leave a mark on the skin resembling its design.\r\n\r\nSince abrasions can result from contact with various surfaces, materials from that surface (like fibers, dirt, or other particles) may become embedded in the abrasion, providing potential evidence in forensic investigations.\r\n\r\nAbrasion typically results due to friction of rough object against skin. Common examples include falling on a rough surface like asphalt or being dragged on the ground.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 189-190.","responses":[{"text":"Contain trace evidence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are caused by friction of rough object against skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leaves scar mark","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiator grill","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Are superficial injuries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13306,"text":"What defines a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 191.","responses":[{"text":"It changes color with time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is caused by a blunt weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous tissue due to blunt trauma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The weapon used can be recognized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may help determine the time of affliction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13308,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding a migratory bruise?","explanation":"A **migratory bruise** refers to the phenomenon where a bruise or ecchymosis **appears away from the actual site of injury**, usually due to the movement of blood along tissue planes or gravitational force. This can be observed in certain injuries where the bleeding from the injury site travels to a dependent location due to the pull of gravity. For example, an injury around the eye (peri-orbital region) can lead to ecchymosis appearing over time in the submandibular region or even the neck.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 192.","responses":[{"text":"May appear away from the impact site","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"May appear immediately","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May appear within hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May appear during re-examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May not appear at all","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13311,"text":"Which of the following is  not true regarding a grinding laceration?","explanation":"A **grinding laceration** typically results from a heavy weight or force that crushes and avulses the skin from the underlying tissues. It is characterized by irregular, torn skin edges and is often associated with significant soft tissue damage and hemorrhage. While such lacerations can occur in road traffic accidents or due to heavy weights, they are not typically the result of a fall from height. A fall from height may result in other types of injuries, but a grinding laceration specifically is more indicative of a crushing force against the tissue.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 196.","responses":[{"text":"Accompanied by extreme extravasation of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caused by heavy weight with avulsion of skin from underlying tissues","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May result in crush syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occurs in road traffic accidents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May result from fall from height","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13312,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect for an incised wound?","explanation":"An **incised wound** is a cut that is longer than it is deep, usually resulting from a sharp-edged object such as a knife, razor, or glass.\r\n\r\nDue to the sharp nature of the weapon or object causing an incised wound, the **edges of the wound are usually clean** and straight, as opposed to the more ragged or irregular edges seen in lacerations or other wound types.\r\n\r\nWhile many incised wounds can be painful due to damage to the skin and underlying tissues, the level of pain experienced can vary depending on factors like the location of the wound, depth, individual pain tolerance, and whether or not any nerves were affected. For instance, wounds that are superficial or that do not involve many nerve endings might not be painful.\r\n\r\nIncised wounds can lead to significant blood loss because of their typically clean and straight nature, which does not encourage immediate blood clotting as might be seen with more jagged wounds.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Bleeds profusely","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A wound with clean edges","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The maximum measurement of an incised wound is its length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is always caused by a sharp weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It Is always painful","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13365,"text":"Which of the following is a disadvantage of the \"food frequency questionnaire\" method of obtaining food intake data?","explanation":"The \"food frequency questionnaire\" (FFQ) is a common method used in nutritional epidemiology to assess the long-term dietary intake of individuals. Like all dietary assessment tools, the FFQ has its advantages and limitations. One of its primary limitations is the potential for both **underestimation or overestimation** of food and nutrient intake. This is because the FFQ relies on the memory and perception of the respondent to recall their typical eating habits over a longer period, and it can be influenced by issues like portion size estimation, forgetfulness about certain foods, or even biases due to perceived social desirability.","reference":"Munoz N, Bernstein M, eds. Nutrition Assessment: Clinical and Research Applications. 1st ed. Jones \u0026 Barlett Learning; 2019: 191.","responses":[{"text":"Influenced by food choices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Underestimation or overestimation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inaccurate nutrient intake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seasonal variability affects result","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ignore long-term changes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13373,"text":"Which of the following is an indicator of a nutritionally at-risk adult?","explanation":"**Involuntary weight loss of ≥ 5%** in a month is an indicator of a nutritionally at-risk adult.\r\n\r\nRapid, involuntary weight loss can be a sign of underlying medical issues or malnutrition. It is essential to investigate the cause, as it might indicate a serious health condition, reduced ability to heal and recover, and increased risk of morbidity and mortality. In the context of assessing nutritional risk, factors like sudden weight changes, especially when unintended, play a crucial role.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Medical Nutrition Therapy, Sub-topic: Calories and Energy.","responses":[{"text":"Voluntary weight gain of 6.5 kg in a month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index less than 25 kg/m²","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental pollution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Involuntary weight loss of ≥ 5% in a month","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Seasonal flu","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13378,"text":"A country in central Africa has high mortality and a high birth rate. The experts wish to classify the country's stage of demographic transition. Which of the following correctly captures the stage of the given country?","explanation":"The demographic transition model describes the progression of countries as they move from high birth and death rates to low birth and death rates through time due to development. The stages of the demographic transition model are as follows:\r\n\r\n**Stage 1 (pre-transitional):** Both high birth and death rates. Population growth is slow and fluctuating. Most societies were in this stage until the late 18th century.\r\n**Stage 2 (early transitional):** Death rates decline due to improvements in food supply and sanitation, leading to population growth. Birth rates remain high.\r\n**Stage 3 (mid-transitional):** Birth rates start to decline due to improved economic conditions, better education, and access to contraception. Population growth starts to moderate.\r\n**Stage 4 (late transitional):** Both birth and death rates are low, balancing each other out. Population growth is minimal or even becomes negative.\r\n**Stage 5 (post-transitional):** Birth rates fall even further, below replacement level, leading to a declining population, though death rates might remain low.\r\n\r\nGiven the described characteristics of the country in central Africa with high mortality and a high birth rate, it would be classified as being in **stage 1 (pre-transitional)** of the demographic transition.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Demography, Sub-topic: Demographic Transition: Stages.","responses":[{"text":"Stage 4 (late transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 5 (post-transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 1 (pre-transitional)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 2 (early transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 3 (mid-transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13381,"text":"A country has a growth rate (r) of 3%. Experts want to make policies for better planning and administration. For this purpose, they want to calculate the number of years needed for the population to double, based on the current growth rate. Which of the following options captures the correct population doubling time of the country, based on the given information?","explanation":"To estimate the doubling time for a population given a constant growth rate, we can use the rule of 70 (also known as the Rule of 70 Doubling Time formula):\r\n\r\nDoubling time (T)= 70/Growth rate (r)\r\n\r\nSo, the population doubling time for the country, based on a growth rate of 3%, is approximately **23.3 years**.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Demography, Sub-topic: Demographic Transition: Stages.","responses":[{"text":"100 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"23.3 years","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"70 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"35 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"140 years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16739,"text":"A man with chronic liver failure due to hepatitis B was brought to the hospital. His imaging reports show regenerative parenchymal nodules with fibrous bands and variable degrees of vascular shunting. Which of the following best describes the mentioned condition?","explanation":"**Cirrhosis** is a late-stage liver disease in which healthy liver tissue is replaced with scar tissue and the liver is permanently damaged. Imaging shows **regenerative parenchymal nodules** with **fibrous bands** and variable degrees of vascular shunting, The scar tissue prevents the liver from working properly. This condition can be caused by various factors, including long-standing hepatitis B infection, as mentioned in the scenario.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 827.","responses":[{"text":"Portal hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non alcoholic fatty liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol intoxication","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16776,"text":"Which of the following is the effect of misoprostol on the gastrointestinal tract?","explanation":"**Misoprostol** is a synthetic prostaglandin E1 analog. It exerts its protective effects on the gastric mucosa by **increasing bicarbonate and mucus secretion**, thus enhancing the mucosal barrier. It also inhibits gastric acid secretion. This makes it useful in the prevention of gastric ulcers in patients taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), which can cause mucosal damage and ulceration.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 510.","responses":[{"text":"Increase in lipid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase B12  absorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in gastric acid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protection of mucosal lining","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocking H2 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17140,"text":"A patient presented to the outpatient department with a history of liver enlargement, pain, hyperbilirubinemia, and ascites. Imaging showed multiple venous thrombi in hepatic veins. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for a patient with liver enlargement, pain, hyperbilirubinemia, ascites, and the presence of multiple venous thrombi in hepatic veins is **Budd-Chiari syndrome**. Budd-Chiari syndrome is a rare disorder characterized by **obstruction of the hepatic veins**, which transport blood from the liver to the inferior vena cava. This obstruction can lead to liver enlargement, pain, and other associated symptoms.\r\n\r\n\r\n- Primary biliary cirrhosis (now more commonly referred to as primary biliary cholangitis) is a chronic disease where the small bile ducts in the liver become inflamed and damaged and are ultimately destroyed. This can lead to a buildup of bile in the liver, causing scarring (cirrhosis). Its clinical picture might include jaundice and ascites, but it would not typically present with hepatic vein thrombi.\r\n\r\nCholelithiasis refers to the formation of gallstones within the gallbladder. While it can cause right upper quadrant pain and jaundice if a stone obstructs the common bile duct, it would not be associated with hepatic vein thrombi.\r\n\r\nPrimary sclerosing cholangitis is a chronic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts. It is not typically associated with hepatic vein thrombi but can show a beaded appearance on imaging due to strictures in the bile ducts.\r\n\r\nFibro-polycystic disease refers to a group of hereditary diseases that can affect the liver, such as polycystic liver disease. They might present with liver enlargement, but the characteristic finding would be cysts in the liver rather than hepatic vein thrombi.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 863.","responses":[{"text":"Fibro-polycystic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Budd-Chiari syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary biliary cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17371,"text":"Which of the following is the side effect of magnesium hydroxide on the gut?","explanation":"**Magnesium hydroxide** is commonly used as an antacid and a laxative. When consumed, it works by drawing water into the intestines from the surrounding tissues. This increase in water content softens and expands the stool, leading to an acceleration of intestinal motility. The result is more frequent bowel movements and a softening of the stool, which is why it is effective as a laxative. However, if taken in excessive amounts or for prolonged periods without adequate hydration, this effect can lead to **diarrhea**.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Gastric irritation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Constipation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignancy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17611,"text":"A woman presents to the emergency department with a complaint of severe abdominal pain, and constipation for a few days. She is a mother to 4 children all born via c-section. What could be the cause of her condition?","explanation":"**Adhesive small bowel disease**, also known as adhesive small bowel obstruction, occurs when the intestines become stuck together or to the wall of the abdomen due to bands of tissue (adhesions) that form after surgery. Given the woman's history of **multiple cesarean sections**, she would be at an increased risk of developing these adhesions, making adhesive small bowel disease a probable diagnosis for her symptoms.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Ulcerative colitis** is a chronic inflammatory condition affecting the colon (large intestine) primarily. It presents with symptoms like diarrhea mixed with blood, abdominal pain, and urgency to defecate. While it can cause abdominal pain, the history provided does not strongly suggest this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nCrohn disease can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from the mouth to the anus. Symptoms can include abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, and fatigue. Like ulcerative colitis, while it can cause abdominal pain, the clinical picture does not align perfectly with the history given.\r\n\r\nInflammatory bowel disease encompasses both ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease. It would not be the most specific diagnosis in this patient.\r\n\r\nWhile abdominal pain and constipation can be symptoms associated with some gastrointestinal malignancies, there is no specific evidence from the provided history that strongly points to a carcinoma.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 777-778.","responses":[{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adhesive small bowel disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18617,"text":"A patient presented to the outpatient department with reports that were positive for viral hepatitis. What type of jaundice can be seen in this patient?","explanation":"In a patient with viral hepatitis, the type of jaundice most commonly seen is **hepatocellular jaundice**. This form of jaundice arises when there is damage to the liver cells, impairing the liver's ability to process bilirubin. Viral hepatitis leads to inflammation and damage of the hepatocytes, which are the liver cells responsible for the metabolism and excretion of bilirubin.\r\n\r\n**Jaundice due to Gilbert syndrome** is a result of a benign hereditary condition that affects the enzyme responsible for processing bilirubin. It's not caused by viral hepatitis or liver damage.\r\n\r\n**Jaundice due to sickle cell disease** is related to hemolysis, or the breakdown of red blood cells, leading to an increase in bilirubin. It is not due to direct liver damage.\r\n\r\n**Obstructive jaundice** is a result of a blockage in the bile ducts, preventing the excretion of bilirubin from the liver to the intestines. It's not typically seen with viral hepatitis unless there's an additional complication.\r\n\r\n**Hemolytic jaundice** arises when there is rapid breakdown of red blood cells, leading to an increased production of bilirubin. It is not directly caused by viral hepatitis.","reference":"Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 29, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544252/","responses":[{"text":"Hemolytic jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jaundice due to Gilbert syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jaundice due to sickle cell disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular jaundice","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18947,"text":"In a clinically stable patient, immediate exploratory laparotomy is indicated in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"In a clinically stable patient, **immediate exploratory laparotomy** is indicated for **penetrating wounds in the thoracoabdominal region.** Such injuries have a high likelihood of damaging internal organs, and timely surgical intervention is crucial to ascertain and repair any internal damage, even if the patient initially appears stable. \r\n\r\nForeign bodies, depending on their nature and location, may or may not require surgical intervention.\r\n\r\nAn intestinal mass on CT requires further diagnostic evaluation.\r\n\r\nFractures typically do not necessitate a laparotomy unless associated with other intra-abdominal injuries.\r\n\r\nPartial obstruction, if stable, may be managed conservatively before considering surgery.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, D24, Gastrointestinal Module, Surgery, Topic: Abdominal Trauma.","responses":[{"text":"Partial obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fractures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetrating wounds in thoracoabdominal reion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Foriegn body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal mass on CT","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20213,"text":"Which of the following is the most relevant statement regarding the H2 receptor blockers?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Nugent CC, Falkson SR, Terrell JM. H2 Blockers. [Updated 2023 Aug 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525994/\r\n(2) Begg M, Tarhuni M, N. Fotso M, et al. Comparing the safety and efficacy of proton pump inhibitors and histamine-2 receptor antagonists in the management of patients with peptic ulcer disease: a systematic review. Cureus. Published August 29, 2023. Accessed January 11, 2024. https://www.cureus.com/articles/163652-comparing-the-safety-and-efficacy-of-proton-pump-inhibitors-and-histamine-2-receptor-antagonists-in-the-management-of-patients-with-peptic-ulcer-disease-a-systematic-review","responses":[{"text":"They cause fastest healing of duodenal ulcers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are most efficacious drug in inhibiting gastric acid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They avoid first pass effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They afford most prompt relief of ulcer pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are commonly used drug to decrease gastric acid secretion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20383,"text":"A 15-year-old boy with suspected acute appendicitis has an Alvarado score of 5-6. Which of the following would be the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","explanation":"The **Alvarado score** is used to stratify the risk of **acute appendicitis** based on clinical findings and laboratory tests. Scores range from 1 to 10. Patients with scores:\r\n\r\n- 1-4 are considered to have a low probability of appendicitis. Observation and reassessment are recommended.\r\n- 5-6 are in a moderate probability category. These patients typically undergo imaging, usually with a **CT scan**, to further evaluate for appendicitis.\r\n- 7-10 are at high probability, and these patients typically go directly to surgery without the need for imaging.","reference":"(1) O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, Sayers RD, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2023: 1341-1342.\r\n  \r\n(2) Ozsoy, Zeki, and Erdinc Yenidogan. “Evaluation of the Alvarado Scoring System in the Management of Acute Appendicitis.” Turkish Journal of Surgery, 8 Sept. 2017, http://www.turkjsurg.com/abstract/1493/eng.","responses":[{"text":"Diagnostic laparoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computerized tomography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Open appendectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clinical management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conservative management","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20397,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents to the emergency department with generalized abdominal pain and board-like rigidity. He has a history of chronic NSAID use.  An abdominal X-ray reveals air under the diaphragm. Which of the following conditions is most likely the cause of this patient's condition?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with generalized abdominal pain, board-like rigidity, and the finding of air under the diaphragm on abdominal X-ray is indicative of **perforation of a hollow viscus** leading to **pneumoperitoneum**. Given the **history of chronic NSAID use**, the most likely cause of this perforation is a **duodenal ulcer rupture**. NSAIDs are well-known risk factors for peptic ulcers, which include both gastric and duodenal ulcers. When these ulcers perforate, they can lead to the release of air into the peritoneal cavity, which can then be detected as free air under the diaphragm on imaging.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Duodenal atresia** is a congenital condition where a part of the duodenum fails to develop properly, leading to an obstruction. Infants with this condition often present with bilious vomiting shortly after birth. It does not cause pneumoperitoneum.\r\n\r\n**Boerhaave lesion**, also known as spontaneous esophageal rupture, is caused by a sudden increase in intra-esophageal pressure, such as during forceful vomiting. While this can lead to air in the mediastinum and potentially the pleural cavity, it does not typically lead to free air under the diaphragm.\r\n\r\n**Gastric ulcer rupture**: Similar to duodenal ulcer rupture, a perforated gastric ulcer can indeed lead to pneumoperitoneum with air under the diaphragm. However, duodenal ulcers are more commonly associated with NSAID use and are more likely to perforate than gastric ulcers.\r\n\r\n**Mallory-Weiss tears**: These are longitudinal mucosal tears at the gastroesophageal junction, commonly associated with persistent vomiting. While they can cause hematemesis (vomiting of blood), they do not result in perforation or air under the diaphragm.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 801.","responses":[{"text":"Duodenal artesia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Boerhaave lesion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory weiss tears","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal ulcer rupture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer rupture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20439,"text":"A 30-year-old male is brought in an unconscious state to the emergency department after a road traffic accident. After regaining consciousness, the patient realizes that he can neither feel nor move his lower limbs. On examination, the gut sounds are absent, and the doctor suspects paralytic ileus. Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's condition?","explanation":"The patient's presentation of being unable to feel or move his lower limbs after a road traffic accident, coupled with the clinical signs of absent gut sounds, points towards a neurological cause of **paralytic ileus**. In this context, the most likely cause of the patient's condition is **spinal cord injury**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nHypokalemia can cause muscle weakness, cramps, and in severe cases, paralysis. However, it would not be the primary suspect in a patient who has just been in a road traffic accident and presents with acute paralysis.\r\n\r\nMesenteric ischemia is a condition where there's reduced blood flow to the intestines due to blockage of the mesenteric arteries. It presents with severe abdominal pain, especially post meals, and not primarily with paralysis.\r\n\r\nColorectal carcinoma would present with signs and symptoms related to the bowel, like change in bowel habits, rectal bleeding, or unexplained weight loss, and not acute paralysis following trauma.\r\n\r\nElevated sodium levels can lead to altered mental status, muscle twitching, and seizures. It does not present with acute paralysis of the lower limbs, especially in the context of a recent traumatic event.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 161.","responses":[{"text":"Colorectal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cord injury","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesenteric ischemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20440,"text":"A 63-year-old male, who is a heavy smoker, complains of food sticking behind his sternum for the last 5 months. He has lost considerable weight and appears malnourished. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy and biopsy confirm the malignant growth. What should be assessed first before commencing the therapy?","explanation":"In a patient with suspected adenocarcinoma of the esophagus, establishing a definitive diagnosis and determining the extent of the disease (staging) is critical before initiating any treatment. \r\n\r\nThe most appropriate investigation before starting treatment for a confirmed case of adenocarcinoma of the esophagus is **CT abdomen and thorax**. This will help in staging the tumor, determining the presence of any metastatic disease, and guiding the therapeutic approach.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nA biopsy is essential to confirm the diagnosis. Tissue is typically obtained during an endoscopic procedure and is then examined under a microscope to determine if cancer cells are present.\r\n\r\nEndoscopy is an essential diagnostic tool for visualizing the tumor and obtaining tissue for biopsy. In esophageal cancer, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) can also be done, which helps determine the depth of tumor invasion and assess for nearby lymph node involvement.\r\n\r\nBarium swallow is a radiographic examination of the esophagus. A patient swallows barium contrast, which outlines the esophagus on X-ray. This can help visualize the location and size of the tumor, but it's less frequently used now because endoscopy and CT scans provide more detailed information.\r\n\r\nUltrasound is not typically the first-line investigation for esophageal cancer. However, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is a specialized form of ultrasound used in esophageal cancer to determine how deeply the tumor has invaded the esophageal wall and whether nearby lymph nodes are affected.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 796.","responses":[{"text":"Peritoneal spread","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan of abdomen and chest","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Distant metastasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multimodal therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General health and nutrition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20834,"text":"In Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP), which of the following gene is mutated?","explanation":"FAP is an autosomal dominant genetic disorder characterized by the presence of numerous adenomatous polyps in the colon and rectum. These polyps are precancerous, and if left untreated, individuals with FAP have a significantly increased risk of developing colorectal cancer at a young age.\r\n\r\nThe **APC** gene is a tumor suppressor gene, and its mutation is the underlying genetic defect in FAP. Mutations in the APC gene lead to the uncontrolled growth of polyps in the colon and rectum, eventually increasing the risk of malignant transformation into colorectal cancer. Therefore, genetic testing for APC gene mutations is crucial in the diagnosis and management of individuals with FAP, as it allows for early intervention and surveillance to prevent the development of cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812.","responses":[{"text":"KRas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MSH-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MLH-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"APC","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"p53","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20903,"text":"Which of the following defines a wound called Jurh Jaifah?","explanation":null,"reference":"Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 27.","responses":[{"text":"Reaching a body cavity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruised margins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Having entry and exit wounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suicidal in nature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Produced by a knife","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21116,"text":"A 50-year-old man has been working in a battery manufacturing factory for the last 10 years. Now he is complaining of weakness, abdominal colic, constipation, and difficulty in walking. On examination, he has anemia, blue lines at the junction of gums and teeth, and foot drop. Which of the following poisoning has most likely occurred in the patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 579.","responses":[{"text":"Mercury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21117,"text":"A 20-year-old girl is working in a chemistry lab. She gets into a quarrel with her fiance, who is also working there, and she takes some poison and she develops abdominal pain, vomiting, and diarrhea. On examination, her vomitus is greenish-blue in color. Which of the following constituent is most likely to be present in the poison she consumed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 581.","responses":[{"text":"Mercury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21118,"text":"The \"term ring\" fracture is used to denote fracture of which of the following structures?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 302.","responses":[{"text":"Pelvic bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen magnum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left Ring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator foraman","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right Ring","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21119,"text":"A 17-year-old man is brought to the emergency department for consumption of acid.  He complained of a burning sensation in his mouth, tingling, and numbness of limbs with constricted pupils. Which of the following acids is the most probable cause of the presentation of the patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 557.","responses":[{"text":"Carbolic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulfuric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxalic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocyanic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salicyclic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21120,"text":"A young man while crossing the road is hit by the vehicle from the side and falls on the road. He is dragged for some distance. Which of the following types of abrasion on the surface of the skin is most likely to develop in this person?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 337.","responses":[{"text":"Imprint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scratch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Graze","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21121,"text":"Defense wounds with sharp weapons are situated in which of the following regions?","explanation":null,"reference":"Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 82.","responses":[{"text":"Precordium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forearms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fingers and palms","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of hands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower limbs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21122,"text":"Which of the following is the primary impact injury in the pedestrian?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 330.","responses":[{"text":"Bumper fracture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bird feet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whiplash","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skull fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jack-knife","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21175,"text":"A 47-year-old man with a history of NSAID-induced ulcers has been placed on sucralfate. Which of the following compounds is related to sucralfate?","explanation":"Sucralfate is an **aluminum salt of sucrose sulfate.** It works by forming a protective barrier at the site of ulcers or erosions in the gastrointestinal tract. When sucralfate comes into contact with gastric acid, it undergoes polymerization to create a sticky, viscous substance that adheres to the damaged mucosal lining of the stomach and duodenum. This protective barrier shields the injured tissue from further damage by acid and pepsin, allowing it to heal.\r\n\r\nThe aluminum in sucralfate binds to the negatively charged proteins in the damaged mucosa, creating a physical barrier that helps to prevent further injury.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 545.","responses":[{"text":"Calcium citrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum sucrose","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium carbonate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium carbonate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21176,"text":"A 49-year-old man with a history of peptic ulcer disease and gastroesophageal reflux disorder has been treated with cimetidine for approximately 20 years. He now complains of breast swelling and breast discharge. Which of the following effects is the most likely explanation for his condition?","explanation":"**Cimetidine** is a histamine H2 receptor antagonist commonly used to reduce gastric acid production, making it effective for conditions like peptic ulcer disease and gastroesophageal reflux disorder (GERD). However, cimetidine also has the side effect of **inhibiting androgen receptors.**\r\n\r\nAndrogen receptors are responsible for the effects of male sex hormones, such as testosterone. When cimetidine inhibits these receptors, it can lead to hormonal imbalances in the body. In males, this can result in gynecomastia, which is characterized by breast swelling and discharge. This condition occurs because cimetidine interferes with the normal hormonal regulation of breast tissue, leading to its growth and secretion.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neoplastic process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overwhelming edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antiandrogenic effect","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21177,"text":"Which of the following drugs is ineffective in combination therapy for the eradication of Helicobacter pylori infection?","explanation":"Helicobacter pylori is a bacterium that colonizes the stomach and can lead to various gastrointestinal issues, including gastritis and peptic ulcers. Combination therapy is often used to eradicate this infection effectively.\r\n\r\nEffective combination therapies usually include antibiotics such as amoxicillin, clarithromycin, and metronidazole, along with bismuth compounds or proton pump inhibitors (PPIs). These combinations target different aspects of the bacterium's life cycle and help ensure successful eradication.\r\n\r\n**Ciprofloxacin**, while effective against many bacterial infections, is not considered a first-line treatment for H. pylori eradication. It is not commonly used in standard combination therapies for this purpose and is not as effective against H. pylori as the antibiotics mentioned above.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 541.","responses":[{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metronidazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bismuth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clarithromycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21178,"text":"Which of the following is the most important drawback of sucralfate in the treatment of duodenal ulcers?","explanation":"Sucralfate is an aluminum-containing medication used to treat duodenal ulcers by forming a protective barrier over the ulcer, promoting healing. However, one of the significant limitations of sucralfate is its dosing frequency. Patients are required to take sucralfate **four times a day,** which can be inconvenient and challenging to adhere to, leading to potential issues with patient compliance.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, other medications for duodenal ulcers, such as proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) or H2-receptor antagonists, often require once-daily dosing, making them more convenient for patients and improving treatment adherence.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 545.","responses":[{"text":"High incidence of side effects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Poor relief of ulcer pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short duration of action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower ulcer healing efficacy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug administration 4 times a day","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21179,"text":"A 56-year-old female is presented to the hospital with an altered level of consciousness. After evaluation, she is diagnosed with fulminant hepatic failure. History reveals jaundice within the recent past. What is the most likely time duration of encephalopathy to develop in this patient?","explanation":"In the context of fulminant hepatic failure, the development of encephalopathy is a critical and rapid event. This condition is characterized by a sudden and severe impairment of liver function, often leading to serious complications including changes in mental status and consciousness. Acute liver failure is associated with encephalopathy and coagulopathy and occurs within 26 weeks (approximately 6 months) of the initial liver injury, particularly in individuals without pre-existing liver disease. The onset of symptoms, including encephalopathy, usually manifests within **two months** of the liver injury. In many cases, the progression of the condition is swift, with patients potentially advancing to coma within just a week of symptom onset. This rapid deterioration underscores the critical nature of acute liver failure and the need for immediate medical intervention.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 826.","responses":[{"text":"Two months","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Two weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Three weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"One year","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"One month","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21180,"text":"A histologist while observing an organ of the oral cavity under a light microscope observed a transition of epithelium from stratified squamous keratinized to non-keratinized epithelium. The core of the organ was made up of muscles. Which of the following is the most likely organ that he might be observing?","explanation":"The **lips** are a prominent feature of the oral cavity and are composed of various tissues, including both keratinized and non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium. The transition from keratinized to non-keratinized epithelium can be observed at different regions of the lips. The outer surface of the lips, which is exposed to external factors and mechanical stress, is typically covered by keratinized stratified squamous epithelium to provide protection. In contrast, the inner mucosal surface of the lips, which is in contact with the oral cavity and food, is lined with non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium for better flexibility and moisture retention.\r\n\r\nThe core of the lips contains muscles responsible for various functions such as speech, expression, and controlling the opening and closing of the oral cavity.","reference":"Mescher, Anthony L., and Luiz Carlos Uchôa Junqueira. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed., McGraw-Hill, 2021: 298","responses":[{"text":"Gingiva","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lips","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cheeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hard palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Soft palate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21181,"text":"A 49-year-old male is admitted to the hospital and is showing signs of impaired neuronal function, rigidity, hyperreflexia, asterixis, and altered level of consciousness. Further history and examination reveal chronic liver disease. Which of the following is the most probable cause of these, manifestations in the patient?","explanation":"This clinical presentation is consistent with hepatic encephalopathy, a neuropsychiatric syndrome that occurs as a complication of liver dysfunction, particularly in cases of cirrhosis or advanced liver disease. In hepatic encephalopathy, the liver's ability to detoxify blood is compromised, leading to **elevated blood levels of ammonia.** Ammonia is neurotoxic and can have detrimental effects on the central nervous system.\r\n\r\nThe elevated ammonia levels can result in various neurological symptoms, including altered consciousness, confusion, asterixis (flapping tremor), and hyperreflexia. These neurological manifestations are characteristic of hepatic encephalopathy and are primarily attributed to the toxic effects of ammonia on the brain.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 827.","responses":[{"text":"Cerebral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased ammonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stroke","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21182,"text":"Which of the following types of polyp can be classified as neoplastic?","explanation":"**Adenomas** are neoplastic polyps that can develop in various organs, including the colon and rectum. These polyps are characterized by the proliferation of glandular epithelial cells and are considered precancerous. Adenomas in the colon are particularly important because they can progress to colorectal cancer over time. \r\n\r\n**Hamartomatous polyps** result from disorganized overgrowth of normal tissues and are generally not considered neoplastic. **Inflammatory polyps** are typically associated with chronic inflammation and are not inherently neoplastic. **Seminomas** are a type of germ cell tumor and are not related to epithelial polyps. **Hyperplastic polyps** are characterized by an overgrowth of normal cells and are generally not considered neoplastic.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 807.","responses":[{"text":"Hamartomatous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplastic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21183,"text":"A 28-year-old male comes to the outpatient department with a history of colicky abdominal pain for 6 months.  Pain is usually associated with diarrhea and abdominal bloating. He denies any history of fever and weight loss. Physical examination is unremarkable. What is the mot likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Irritable Bowel Syndrome** is a common gastrointestinal disorder characterized by recurrent abdominal pain or discomfort, typically associated with altered bowel habits, including diarrhea, constipation, or a combination of both. The abdominal pain in IBS is often described as colicky and relieved by defecation. Patients may also experience bloating and a sense of incomplete evacuation.\r\n\r\nThe absence of fever and weight loss, along with the presence of normal physical examination findings, makes IBS a more likely diagnosis compared to conditions like Inflammatory Bowel Disease or Ischemic Colitis, which often present with systemic symptoms and abnormal physical examination findings. Peptic ulcer and reflux esophagitis typically manifest with symptoms related to the upper gastrointestinal tract, such as heartburn and epigastric pain, rather than lower abdominal symptoms like diarrhea and bloating.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 824, 825.","responses":[{"text":"Reflux esophagiits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21184,"text":"A 25-year-old female presents to the hospital with loose stools for 3 years. On examination, she is anemic, has glossitis, and marked weight loss. Investigations reveal Hemoglobin (Hb( 9 g/dl, mean corpuscular volume (MCV) 70. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy with biopsy shows subtotal villous atrophy with intra-epithelial lymphocyte infiltrates. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Celiac disease,** also known as gluten-sensitive enteropathy, is an autoimmune disorder triggered by the ingestion of gluten-containing foods in genetically predisposed individuals. It primarily affects the small intestine, leading to the malabsorption of nutrients. The classic clinical features include chronic diarrhea, weight loss, anemia (as a result of malabsorption), and glossitis.\r\n\r\nThe diagnostic gold standard for celiac disease is the biopsy of the small intestine, which typically reveals villous atrophy and increased intra-epithelial lymphocytes. This biopsy finding, along with clinical symptoms and laboratory results such as anemia and low MCV, is highly suggestive of celiac disease.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 806.","responses":[{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV enteropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tropical sprue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21299,"text":"A family member of a patient demands the doctor to withhold crucial medical information from the patient to protect him from emotional distress. What would be the most likely way to handle the situation?","explanation":"Medical ethics and principles emphasize the importance of honesty and transparency in patient care. While it's natural for family members to have concerns about the emotional well-being of their loved ones, the patient has the fundamental right to be informed about their own medical condition. It is important to explain to the family member that withholding critical medical information from the patient could compromise their autonomy and trust in the healthcare team.\r\n\r\nThe next step is to **involve the patient in the discussion.** Assess the patient's preferences regarding the disclosure of information and respect their autonomy. Patients may have different coping mechanisms, and some may want to be fully informed, while others may prefer a more gradual disclosure. By involving the patient, you empower them to make decisions about their own healthcare and help build trust in the physician-patient relationship.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Behavioral Science lecture, Breaking of Bad News, Gastrointestinal-2, Slide 8.","responses":[{"text":"Document the request and keep the patient involved privately","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leave the room and let the nursing staff explain the situation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Consult your colleagues to make a decision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Comply with the family member's request to maintain trust","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Explain the importance of honesty and involve patient in the discussion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21303,"text":"A 3-year-old male child presents with a history of constipation and abdominal distension for the last few years. The plain abdominal X-ray reveals fecal matter contained distended bowel loops. A barium study shows a transitional zone at the rectosigmoid junction. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hirschsprung's disease** is a congenital condition characterized by the absence of ganglion cells in the submucosal and myenteric plexuses of the distal bowel, which leads to a functional obstruction of the affected bowel segment. This absence of ganglion cells typically occurs in the rectosigmoid region, as indicated by the transitional zone observed in the barium study.\r\n\r\nThe absence of ganglion cells results in impaired peristalsis and a failure to relax the affected bowel segment, leading to the accumulation of stool, constipation, and abdominal distension. This condition is commonly diagnosed in infancy or early childhood when symptoms become apparent.","reference":"Smith M, Chhabra S, Shukla R, et al. The transition zone in Hirschsprung's bowel contains abnormal hybrid ganglia with characteristics of extrinsic nerves. J Cell Mol Med. 2023;27(2):287-298. doi:10.1111/jcmm.17659","responses":[{"text":"Malrotation of gut","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital megacolon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small intestinal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hirschsprung's disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21304,"text":"A 5-month-old child presents with a history of recurrent vomiting mostly after feed but never containing blood. He is on mother feed with alternate bottle feed. He is admitted to hospital due to vomiting. He was a full-term baby and his birth weight was 2.7 Kg. On examination, the child is irritable with a current weight of 3.1 Kg and bilateral mild crepitations. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)** is a common condition in infants characterized by the regurgitation of stomach contents into the esophagus due to the immaturity of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) and the predominantly liquid diet of infants. In this case, the child's recurrent vomiting, especially after feeds, is a classic symptom of GERD. It typically occurs without blood in the vomit.\r\n\r\nThe irritability and poor weight gain in the child can be attributed to the discomfort caused by the reflux of stomach acid and partially digested food into the esophagus, which can interfere with feeding and lead to inadequate weight gain.","reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2018: 271.","responses":[{"text":"Gastroesophageal reflux disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rumination disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal diverticula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilic esophagitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptic ulcer disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21305,"text":"a 26-year-old female is suspected of having acute appendicitis. On examination, he experiences abdominal pain during extension of right hip while lying on the left lateral posiition. Where do you suspect the location of the tip of her appendix?","explanation":"In cases of acute appendicitis, the inflammation of the appendix can cause pain and tenderness in the lower right abdomen. The exact location of the appendix can vary, but there are several possible positions. The **retrocecal** position is one of them, where the appendix is situated behind the cecum, which is the beginning of the large intestine. This retrocecal location can make the diagnosis of appendicitis a bit more challenging because the pain and tenderness may not follow the classic pattern.\r\n\r\nThe specific finding of pain during extension of the right hip while the patient is lying on the left lateral position, known as the psoas sign, is indicative of retrocecal appendicitis. It occurs when the inflamed appendix irritates the psoas muscle, causing pain when the hip is extended.","reference":"Rastogi, Vaibhav, et al. “Abdominal Physical Signs and Medical Eponyms: Movements and Compression.” Clinical Medicine \u0026 Research, Dec. 2018, http://www.clinmedres.org/lookup/doi/10.3121/cmr.2018.1422.","responses":[{"text":"Retrocecal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pre-ileal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypogastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-ileal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21306,"text":"Which of the following inhibits the release of gastrin from the G cells in the antrum of the stomach?","explanation":"Gastrin is a hormone responsible for stimulating gastric acid secretion in the stomach. Its release is tightly regulated to maintain proper acid balance and digestive processes. When the **pH in the upper small intestine is low (acidic),** it serves as a feedback mechanism to inhibit the further release of gastrin. This mechanism is important in preventing excessive gastric acid production and maintaining the optimal pH environment for digestion and absorption in the small intestine.","reference":"Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 364.","responses":[{"text":"Vagal stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low pH in upper small intestine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distension of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22092,"text":"In response to undernutrition, the hypothalamus regulates the energy balance by suppressing which of the following?","explanation":"The hypothalamus contains specialized neurons that produce neuropeptides like orexigenic neuropeptide Y (NPY) and anorexigenic alpha-melanocyte-stimulating hormone (α-MSH), which are essential in controlling hunger and **satiety**. In response to undernutrition, the hypothalamus adjusts the secretion of these neuropeptides to increase hunger signals and decrease satiety signals. This adjustment aims to increase food intake and conserve energy. The interaction between long-term signals like leptin and short-term signals within the hypothalamus ensures the regulation of meal size and frequency in relation to the body's energy stores. Loss-of-function mutations in the melanocortin-4 receptor (MC4R), which α-MSH binds to, are associated with early-onset obesity.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 353.","responses":[{"text":"Glycogenolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Satiety","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat accumulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reproduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22093,"text":"An 8-year-old child is nutritionally deficient and is diagnosed to be suffering from marasmus. Which of the following is most relevant about his condition?","explanation":"Marasmus is a form of severe malnutrition characterized primarily by energy deficiency. An 8-year-old child suffering from marasmus would typically present with significant weight loss or failure to gain weight appropriately for their age. One of the hallmark features of marasmus is the **absence of edema,** which differentiates it from kwashiorkor, another severe form of malnutrition where edema is present due to protein deficiency. In the case of marasmus, the child’s body weight is significantly reduced due to the depletion of both fat and muscle. This absence of edema, combined with other signs such as muscle wasting, growth retardation, and a general emaciated appearance, helps in diagnosing marasmus.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 369.","responses":[{"text":"Enlarged liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Good appetite","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Edema absent","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal height","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal weight","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22094,"text":"A 9-month-old child was admitted for the second time to a nearby tertiary care hospital in Dadu, Sindh with severe abdominal cramps, and fever. He looked pale and skinny. The yellow-colored conjunctivae showed he had jaundice. Upon biochemical estimations of his blood profile, and liver function tests his bilirubin came out to be 21 mg/dl. The child is not responding to phenobarbital and sunlight exposure therapies. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Crigler-Najjar syndrome** is a rare inherited disorder characterized by impaired bilirubin conjugation, leading to the accumulation of unconjugated bilirubin in the blood. In Crigler-Najjar syndrome **type I**, there is a severe deficiency or absence of the enzyme uridine diphosphate glucuronosyltransferase 1A1 (UGT1A1), which is responsible for conjugating bilirubin in the liver. This severe deficiency results in extremely high levels of unconjugated bilirubin in the blood, leading to jaundice and its associated symptoms.","reference":"Singh A, Koritala T, Jialal I. Unconjugated Hyperbilirubinemia. [Updated 2023 Feb 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549796/","responses":[{"text":"Crigler-Najjar syndrome I","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crigler-Najjar syndrome II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gilbert syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotor syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22095,"text":"A 20-year-old woman visited the tertiary hospital in Karachi. The biochemical findings showed that her conjugated serum bilirubin levels were elevated. Her skin, nails, and eyes were yellowish. Later she was diagnosed with Dubin-Johnson syndrome. What is the cause of Dubin-Johnson syndrome?","explanation":"Dubin-Johnson syndrome is a rare inherited disorder characterized by elevated conjugated (direct) bilirubin levels in the blood, leading to jaundice. Conjugated bilirubin is normally excreted into the bile and then into the intestine, but in individuals with Dubin-Johnson syndrome, there is a mutation in the **MRP-2 (Multidrug Resistance-Associated Protein 2) protein**, which is responsible for transporting conjugated bilirubin from the liver into the bile.\r\n\r\nThe deficiency or dysfunction of MRP-2 results in impaired bilirubin excretion, causing the accumulation of conjugated bilirubin in the liver. This accumulation leads to jaundice, with yellowing of the skin, nails, and eyes, as observed in the patient.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 854.","responses":[{"text":"Deficiency in uridine glucosyl transferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deficiency of aspartate aminotransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mutation in MRP-2 protein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deficiency of glucose-6 phosphate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deficiency of Alanine aminotransferase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22096,"text":"A 20-year-old man was admitted to a local hospital in Shikarpur city with Jaundice. His skin and conjunctivae were yellow. His biochemical findings showed the presence of Indirect, serum-unconjugated bilirubin (4 mg/dl), increased urine urobilinogen, and fecal stercobilinogen. However, the thymol turbidity test and liver enzyme levels were normal. What is the most likely type of jaundice the patient is suffering from?","explanation":"**Prehepatic jaundice,** also known as hemolytic jaundice, occurs when there is an excessive breakdown of red blood cells, leading to the release of large amounts of unconjugated bilirubin into the bloodstream. In this type of jaundice, the liver is functioning normally, but it is overwhelmed by the increased bilirubin production. \r\n\r\nThe patient's biochemical findings support the diagnosis of prehepatic jaundice. The presence of high levels of indirect, serum-unconjugated bilirubin, increased urine urobilinogen, and fecal stercobilinogen all indicate that the excess bilirubin is coming from the breakdown of red blood cells, and the liver is unable to process it efficiently. Additionally, normal thymol turbidity test and liver enzyme levels suggest that the liver itself is not the primary source of the problem.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 284.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prehepatic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posthepatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholestatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22097,"text":"If a country uses such a method to conduct a census that only represents people who legally \"belong\" to a given area in some way or another, regardless of whether they were there on the day of census. Which of the following options best expresses the above method of counting?","explanation":"**De jure** means \"by law.\" In the context of census, it involves counting individuals based on their legal residence or affiliation with a particular area, such as a country or region. People are included in the census if they have a legal connection to the designated area, even if they are not physically present at the time of the census. This method is often used for official population counts and for determining representation, resource allocation, and electoral boundaries.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **De facto** refers to counting individuals based on their actual physical presence in the area at the time of the census, regardless of their legal status. A combination of both methods may also be used in some cases, with exceptions made for certain groups or individuals who do not fit neatly into either category.","reference":"D'24, Community Medicine Lecture slides, demographic measurements, census.","responses":[{"text":"De jure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"De facto","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"De jure method with some exceptions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"De facto method with some exceptions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Combination of De facto and De jure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22098,"text":"A country had a sharp decline in births but that still did not bring an immediate reduction in the Natural Increase. Which one of the following options best expresses this phenomenon?","explanation":"**Population momentum** refers to the continued population growth that occurs even after a significant decline in birth rates. It occurs because of the age structure of the population. When there is a large proportion of young people in the population, even a reduced birth rate can result in a substantial number of births because many individuals are of childbearing age. This phenomenon takes time to reverse, as it depends on the aging of the population.\r\n\r\nIn this situation, while the birth rate has decreased, the large number of individuals in the childbearing age group continues to contribute to the overall population growth for some time. Eventually, as the population ages and the proportion of young people decreases, population growth will slow down.","reference":"Dow D'24 lecture slides, Demography.","responses":[{"text":"Population Dynamics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population Momentum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Population Pyramid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population Transition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population Growth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22099,"text":"A pediatrician asks a medical student to read aloud the anthropometric measures from the file of a 3-year-old boy patient in the ward. To fulfill this task, the student will read out which of the following?","explanation":"**Body weight** is one of the key anthropometric measures used to monitor a child's growth and nutritional status. It provides valuable information about the child's overall health and can help identify potential issues such as malnutrition or obesity.\r\n\r\nIn the case of a 3-year-old boy, tracking his body weight over time is crucial for assessing whether he is growing appropriately for his age. The medical student will report this measurement as part of the routine examination, allowing the pediatrician to evaluate the child's growth pattern and make informed decisions regarding his health and nutritional needs.","reference":"Ilyas M. Public Health and Community Medicine. 8th ed. Time Publisher; 2016: 384.","responses":[{"text":"X-ray finding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body weight","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine report","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22101,"text":"According to the Gomez classification, all cases of edema are considered which grade of\r\nProtein Energy Malnutrition (PEM)?","explanation":"In the Gomez classification of Protein Energy Malnutrition (PEM), cases with edema are considered as part of the most severe category, reflecting an advanced state of malnutrition. This classification considers the presence of edema as a critical indicator of nutritional status and categorizes such cases as **3rd degree** malnutrition, also known as severe or marasmic-kwashiorkor. The 3rd degree of PEM is characterized by severe wasting of body fat and muscle, and the presence of edema adds to the complexity and severity of the condition. This stage of PEM requires immediate and intensive nutritional and medical intervention due to the high risk of complications and mortality.","reference":"D'26 Lecture slides, community medicine lecture ''Protein Energy Malnutrition''","responses":[{"text":"1st degree","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd degree","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Underweight","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluid retention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd degree","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22102,"text":"A mother visits the primary healthcare center with her two-year-old child and complains that the child does not eat well and is lethargic. On examination, the child has sparse easily pluckable golden-brown hair, puffy eyes, edema, relatively thin limbs, and protruded belly, along with skin rash. The child is most likely a case of which of the following?","explanation":"The child's presentation is consistent with **Kwashiorkor**. Kwashiorkor is a severe form of malnutrition that primarily occurs due to inadequate protein intake, often in the presence of a sufficient or even excess calorie intake from carbohydrates. \r\n\r\nThe key clinical features of Kwashiorkor include edema, which is a hallmark sign and is often generalized, leading to swelling of the body, puffy eyes, and a protruded belly. Additionally, affected children may have sparse, easily pluckable hair, which becomes brittle and loses its normal texture. Skin changes are also common, including rashes, hyperpigmentation, and desquamation. Furthermore, Kwashiorkor can lead to lethargy and irritability, resulting in overall weakness and irritability in affected children.\r\n\r\nUnlike Marasmus, which is characterized by severe calorie deficiency leading to wasting and a skeletal appearance, Kwashiorkor primarily results from a lack of protein in the diet, even when calorie intake may be relatively adequate.","reference":"D'26 lecture slides, community medicine ''Protein Energy Malnutrition''.","responses":[{"text":"Marasmus and Kwashiorkor combination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marasmus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Micronutrient deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kwashiorkor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Overweight","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22106,"text":"A scientist suggested the provincial government to\"establish a system to continuously monitor the dietary intake and nutritional status of selected population groups. He planned to use a variety of data-collection methods with an ultimate goal of policy formulation and action planning and improving population health\". The suggestion by the scientist best corresponds to which of the following?","explanation":"**Nutritional surveillance** is a systematic and continuous process of collecting, analyzing, and interpreting data related to dietary intake and the nutritional status of specific population groups over time. Its primary objective is to monitor changes in nutritional patterns, identify trends, and assess the effectiveness of nutrition-related policies and interventions. \r\n\r\nIn this case, the scientist's proposal to establish a system for continuous monitoring of dietary intake and nutritional status for policy formulation and population health improvement reflects the core principles of nutritional surveillance. It involves the use of various data-collection methods, including surveys, assessments, and data analysis, to track and respond to the nutritional needs and challenges within the population.","reference":"World Health Organization's (WHO) definition of nutritional surveillance\r\nhttps://iris.who.int/bitstream/handle/10665/264918/PMC2536157.pdf","responses":[{"text":"Food safety","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional research","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Food security","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional surveillance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional assessment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22110,"text":"A 30-year-old man presented to his primary care physician the results of his recent screening, which he did for an overseas job. The lab shows the presence of Anti- Hepatitis C antibody. Which of the following further tests should be advised?","explanation":"The presence of Anti-Hepatitis C antibodies indicates exposure to the Hepatitis C virus (HCV) at some point. However, it doesn't provide information about the current status of the infection. To determine if the individual is currently infected with HCV and **to assess the viral load, the HCV RNA test is necessary.** This test detects the genetic material of the virus in the blood and quantifies the amount of virus present. It helps in confirming active infection and assessing the viral load, which is essential for making treatment decisions.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 877.","responses":[{"text":"Ultrasound Abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete Blood Count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver Function Tests (LFTs)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C genotype","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C Viral Load (HCV RNA)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22111,"text":"A 20-year-old man presented to the medical specialist with complaints of yellow discoloration of the eyes for one week. Along with this, he complained of a fever and vomiting. He has a history of using un-boiled water. Which of the following initial tests should be ordered?","explanation":"Jaundice can be a manifestation of various liver diseases, including viral hepatitis. Given the patient's symptoms and exposure history, testing for **hepatitis viruses** is crucial, as these viruses are transmitted through contaminated water or food, fitting the patient's history of using un-boiled water.\r\n\r\n**Liver Function Tests (LFT)** will help assess the overall function and health of the liver and may provide valuable information about the severity and nature of the liver involvement. Elevated levels of liver enzymes (such as ALT and AST) and bilirubin can indicate liver dysfunction.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 872.","responses":[{"text":"Urinalysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LFT and Serological Test for Hepatitis A \u0026 E","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood Culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete Blood Count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal Ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22114,"text":"A 45-year-old man presents to the family physician with complaints of pain in the abdomen, especially in the right hypochondriac region. The pain has been associated with high-grade fever for 7 days. Ultrasound abdomen shows a liver abscess size of 10 cm x 8 cm. What treatment is recommended for his illness?","explanation":"Liver abscesses can result from various causes, including bacterial and, less commonly, fungal infections. In most cases, the primary treatment involves **antibiotics** to target the underlying infection. In addition to antibiotics, **drainage of the abscess** may be necessary to remove the pus and alleviate symptoms.\r\n\r\nSurgical resection of the liver abscess is typically reserved for specific cases where percutaneous drainage is not feasible or fails to resolve the abscess adequately. Antifungal medications would only be considered if there were strong indications of a fungal etiology, which is less common in liver abscesses compared to bacterial causes. Intravenous fluids and pain management are supportive measures but do not address the underlying infection or abscess drainage.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 880.","responses":[{"text":"Antifungal medications","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotics only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surgical resection of the liver abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous fluids and pain management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotics with ultrasound-guided percutaneous drainage","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22115,"text":"A 16-year-old boy arrived at the medical emergency department with loose motions for six months. On examination, he appears frail and malnourished. His complete blood count (CBC) reveals HB 5 g/dl, MCV 60 fl, platelet counts 5 lacs, and WBC 4000/cubic mm. Which of the following tests is recommended to diagnose the cause of his diarrhea?","explanation":"**Celiac disease** can manifest at various ages and is known to cause a wide range of gastrointestinal and systemic symptoms, including chronic diarrhea, malabsorption of nutrients, anemia (as evidenced by the low hemoglobin level and microcytosis indicated by MCV 60 fl), and growth failure.\r\n\r\nThe **serum celiac disease panel,** which includes the measurement of anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies, is a key diagnostic tool for identifying coeliac disease.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 806.","responses":[{"text":"Colonoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool culture for bacterial pathogens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum celiac disease panel (anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool ova and parasite examination","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22116,"text":"A 20-year-old man presents to the medical OPD with complaints of diarrhea, and abdominal cramps for two days. They are watery in consistency and associated with blood in stool. On examination, he has a pulse of 100/min, a B.P. of 100/70 mm temperature of 101°F, and looks dehydrated. Which of the following is the most likely organism causing his illness?","explanation":"*Campylobacter* is a gram-negative bacterium that is known to cause **enterocolitis,** characterized by symptoms such as diarrhea, abdominal cramps, fever, and occasionally, blood in the stool. The clinical presentation of this patient, including watery diarrhea with blood, abdominal cramps, fever, and signs of dehydration, is typical of a Campylobacter infection.\r\n\r\nEnterocolitis caused by Campylobacter often begins with watery diarrhea, which can progress to bloody stools and severe abdominal pain. The patient's vital signs, such as an elevated pulse, low blood pressure, and fever, are indicative of dehydration, a common complication of diarrheal illnesses.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 155.","responses":[{"text":"Shigella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotavirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli (E. coli)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Campylobacter","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22117,"text":"A 40-year-old male patient presents to the clinic with loss of appetite, nausea, and weight loss for the last 08 months. His lab reports reveal SGPT 120, HbeAg reactive \u0026 HBV viral load 20,000. ultrasound abdomen is unremarkable. He is diagnosed with chronic HBV infection. Which of the drugs is used as first-line treatment of chronic HBV infection?","explanation":"**Tenofovir** is a potent antiviral medication that belongs to a class of drugs known as nucleoside/nucleotide analogs. It inhibits the replication of the hepatitis B virus, reducing the viral load in the body and slowing down the progression of liver disease.\r\n\r\nOther antiviral drugs like Lamivudine were used in the past, but Tenofovir is now considered the preferred first-line therapy due to its higher potency and lower risk of drug resistance.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 876.","responses":[{"text":"Daclatasvir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenofovir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peg IFN","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sofosbuvir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22118,"text":"A 38-year-old female patient with gestational amenorrhea for 32 weeks presents in the ER with a sudden development of jaundice followed by an altered level of consciousness. On examination, she is hemodynamically stable, and deeply jaundiced, but not oriented in time, place, and person.  LFT shows marked Increased serum bilirubin with a marked increase in ALT, and AST levels. Which of the viral infections is more likely to be the cause of her rapid deterioration?","explanation":"**Hepatitis E virus (HEV)**  infection can lead to severe complications in pregnant women, especially during the third trimester. This condition is known as fulminant hepatic failure (FHF) or acute liver failure, which is characterized by a sudden and rapid deterioration in liver function.\r\n\r\nHEV is transmitted through the fecal-oral route, and it is particularly common in regions with inadequate sanitation and hygiene practices. Pregnant women are at higher risk of severe HEV infection, and it can result in serious liver damage, leading to jaundice and altered consciousness.\r\n\r\nThe marked increase in serum bilirubin, ALT, and AST levels seen in this patient is consistent with the liver dysfunction commonly observed in acute viral hepatitis. However, in this case, the rapid progression of symptoms and the patient's pregnancy history make Hepatitis E the most likely culprit.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 878.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis E","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22119,"text":"A 42-year-old male, smoker, obese, came to a gastroenterologist with a recurrent history of epigastric pain and retrosternal burning not responding to conventional treatment, taken for the last 4-6 weeks. He planned an upper GI endoscopy which showed reddish longitudinal lesions extending above the Z-line, and multiple biopsies were taken. Biopsy showed Columnar metaplasia in the esophagus. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"**Barrett's esophagus** is characterized by the replacement of the normal squamous epithelium of the lower esophagus with specialized columnar epithelium containing goblet cells. This condition is often associated with chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). In patients with Barrett's esophagus, the chronic exposure to stomach acid can lead to cellular changes in the esophageal lining, which is considered a premalignant condition.\r\n\r\nThe reddish longitudinal lesions seen during upper GI endoscopy are a key indicator of Barrett's esophagus. Biopsies are typically taken to confirm the presence of columnar metaplasia and to assess the degree of dysplasia, which can range from low-grade to high-grade. Patients with Barrett's esophagus have an increased risk of developing esophageal adenocarcinoma, so regular surveillance and management are essential to monitor and reduce this risk.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 792, 793.","responses":[{"text":"Achalasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hiatal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barrett's esophagus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal candidiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22123,"text":"A 28-year-old male came into the emergency department with a one-day history of loose stools\r\nand vomiting. He had ten episodes of loose stools overnight. On examination, he is dehydrated, lethargic, and unable to take oral ORS. He passed one stool in the emergency department which is watery in appearance. What is the fluid of choice for dehydration correction in this patient?","explanation":"**Normal Saline,** also known as 0.9% Sodium Chloride (NaCl), is an isotonic solution, meaning it has a similar concentration of salt as the body's cells and extracellular fluid. This makes it ideal for rapidly restoring intravascular volume and correcting dehydration. \r\n\r\nIn cases of acute gastroenteritis with significant fluid loss through vomiting and diarrhea, Normal Saline helps replenish lost fluids and electrolytes like sodium and chloride. It is especially crucial when the patient is unable to take oral rehydration solutions (ORS) due to vomiting or lethargy, as it can be administered intravenously to quickly restore fluid balance and correct dehydration.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 303.","responses":[{"text":"Lactated ringer (R/L)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal saline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dextrose water","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dextrose saline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22209,"text":"A 35-year-old woman complained of a month-long, off-and-on burning pain in her upper abdomen, which was moderately intense. She also experienced nausea and had vomited once. There were no signs of black, bloody stools, or vomiting blood. Biopsy results showed she had an H. pylori infection. What are the specific conditions needed to culture H. pylori?","explanation":"The correct condition for culturing H. pylori is **microaerophilic**, which means it needs lower levels of oxygen (around 5-10% oxygen) than the atmospheric concentration (approximately 21% oxygen) to grow optimally. Additionally, H. pylori prefers a **higher carbon dioxide (CO2) concentration** than what is present in ambient air, typically around **5% CO2**, which helps create a suitable microenvironment for its growth.","reference":"Andersen LP, Wadström T. Basic Bacteriology and Culture. In: Mobley HLT, Mendz GL, Hazell SL, editors. Helicobacter pylori: Physiology and Genetics. Washington (DC): ASM Press; 2001. Chapter 4. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2444/","responses":[{"text":"0.5% CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaerobic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.1% CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aerobic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microaerophilic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22211,"text":"Which microorganism is most likely responsible for the gram-negative bacillary infection found in the histologic evaluation of biopsy specimens from a 49-year-old woman with worsening epigastric pain and a 4-mm duodenal ulcer identified during upper endoscopy, despite no evidence of malignancy?","explanation":"*Helicobacter pylori* is a well-known bacterium associated with various gastrointestinal disorders, including **peptic ulcers.**\r\n\r\nThis bacterium colonizes the gastric and duodenal mucosa, causing inflammation and damage to the epithelial lining, which can lead to the development of ulcers. In the case of the 49-year-old woman with worsening epigastric pain and a duodenal ulcer, the presence of Helicobacter pylori is a common culprit.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 770.","responses":[{"text":"Klebsiella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterobacter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicobacter pylori","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus Pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22212,"text":"A hospital admitted a 16-year-old girl who had symptoms such as fever, loss of appetite, feeling sick to her stomach, throwing up, and signs of jaundice like yellowing of the skin and dark urine, as well as pale-colored stool. When her blood was tested, it showed higher levels of certain liver enzymes. Upon further Inquiry, it was discovered that she had recently eaten fast food at a nearby restaurant. Laboratory tests confirmed the presence of IgM HAV antibodies. The virus is transmitted through which of the following?","explanation":"**HAV** is a highly contagious virus that primarily affects the liver. When an infected person prepares or handles food without proper hygiene, the virus can **contaminate the food or water**, and if ingested by another individual, it can lead to infection. Symptoms of HAV infection include fever, nausea, vomiting, jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes), dark urine, and pale-colored stools, which are consistent with the clinical presentation of the girl.\r\n\r\nUnlike some other hepatitis viruses (such as hepatitis B and C), HAV is not transmitted through blood, airborne droplets, semen, or needle sticks.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 831.","responses":[{"text":"Needle stick","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airborne droplets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contaminated water","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Semen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22213,"text":"Which of the following serologic tests is most likely to be positive in patients suffering from chronic diarrhea due to celiac disease?","explanation":"Celiac disease, also known as gluten-sensitive enteropathy, is an autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. **Antigliadin antibodies** are directed against gliadin, a component of gluten found in wheat, barley, and rye. While testing for antigliadin antibodies was historically a common practice, it's important to note that newer serological tests, like anti-tissue transglutaminase (tTG) and anti-endomysial antibodies (EMA), are now more commonly used due to their higher specificity and sensitivity. These antibodies are indicative of the body's immune response to gluten ingestion and are used in conjunction with clinical findings and other diagnostic procedures, such as intestinal biopsy, to confirm the diagnosis of celiac disease. Nonetheless, the presence of antigliadin antibodies can still be supportive of the diagnosis in this clinical context.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 784.","responses":[{"text":"Antigliadin antibody","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anticentomeric antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti DNA topoisomerase I antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antinuclear antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antimitochondrial antibody","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22214,"text":"A 27-year-old man comes to the emergency room with symptoms of acute intestinal obstruction. Examination reveals fever and a mass in the right lower abdominal quadrant. The patient subsequently undergoes surgery, and a segmental lesion involving the terminal ileum is resected showing a thickened wall and loss of mucosal regular folds. Mesenteric adipose tissue seems to creep over bowel loops. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Crohn's disease** is a chronic inflammatory bowel disease characterized by transmural inflammation, which means it affects the entire thickness of the intestinal wall. The condition often presents with symptoms of abdominal pain, fever, and intestinal obstruction due to the thickening of the bowel wall, as described in the patient's presentation.\r\n\r\nKey pathological features of Crohn's disease include skip lesions, which means that inflamed segments of the bowel are interspersed with normal segments. The inflammation can involve any part of the gastrointestinal tract, from the mouth to the anus, but it most commonly affects the terminal ileum. The loss of mucosal regular folds and creeping of mesenteric adipose tissue over bowel loops, as observed during surgery, are also characteristic findings of Crohn's disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Carcinoid tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomembranous colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22215,"text":"Salmonella typhi and Salmonella paratyphi A and B are bacteria that can cause severe illness by crossing the intestinal lining in humans, ultimately reaching the body's immune system. After an incubation period of 8 to 14 days, they trigger a systemic infection. What is the term used to quantify the level of pathogenicity of the organisms?","explanation":"**Virulence** refers to the degree of pathogenicity exhibited by a microorganism. It assesses how effectively a pathogen can cause disease and harm the host. In the case of Salmonella typhi and related strains, their virulence factors allow them to overcome the host's defenses, cross the intestinal lining, and establish a systemic infection. These bacteria have specific mechanisms, such as adhesion molecules and toxins, that enable them to invade host tissues and evade the immune response.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 31.","responses":[{"text":"Resistance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pathogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Virulence","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22216,"text":"A 35-year-old man experienced sudden nausea, vomiting, and extensive diarrhea with watery stools, about 5 liters/day. These symptoms led to dehydration, circulatory collapse, and anuria (lack of urine production) due to the rapid loss of fluids and electrolytes. Which of the following bacterium is the most likely cause?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms of sudden nausea, vomiting, extensive watery diarrhea (up to 5 liters per day), dehydration, circulatory collapse, and anuria are characteristic of **cholera**, a disease primarily caused by *Vibrio cholerae*. \r\n\r\n*Vibrio cholerae* produces cholera toxin, which is responsible for the profuse watery diarrhea seen in cholera cases. This toxin stimulates the secretion of chloride and water into the intestinal lumen, leading to the massive fluid loss observed in affected individuals. The rapid loss of fluids and electrolytes can result in severe dehydration and circulatory collapse, as described in this case.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 154.","responses":[{"text":"Shigella dysenteriae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterotoxigenic E.coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Campylobacter jejuni","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella typhimurium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vibrio cholera","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22389,"text":"Which of the following is the most common primary liver cancer?","explanation":"**Hepatocellular carcinoma** is a malignancy that arises from hepatocytes, the main functional cells of the liver. It accounts for a significant proportion of all liver cancer cases worldwide. Several risk factors contribute to the development of HCC, including chronic hepatitis B and C infections, cirrhosis, alcohol abuse, and exposure to aflatoxins.\r\n\r\nAngiosarcoma is a malignant tumor of blood vessels within the liver, hepatocellular adenoma is a benign tumor of hepatocytes, cavernous hemangiomas are benign vascular lesions, and hepatoblastoma is a rare malignant tumor that primarily affects children.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020:  867.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatoblastoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular Adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiosarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cavernous hemangiomas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22390,"text":"A middle-aged female has recently gone through Endoscopy due to gastroesophageal reflux disease. Metaplastic change whereby squamous epithelium is replaced by\r\ncolumnar epithelium due to prolonged injury occurs in which of the following?","explanation":"**Barrett's esophagus** is a premalignant condition that occurs as a result of chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). Prolonged exposure of the lower esophagus to gastric acid and digestive enzymes leads to damage to the squamous epithelium lining the esophagus. In response to this injury, the body undergoes metaplastic changes, replacing the normal squamous epithelium with columnar epithelium that resembles the lining of the stomach or intestines.\r\n\r\nBarrett's esophagus is of particular concern because it increases the risk of developing **esophageal adenocarcinoma**. Patients with Barrett's esophagus require regular surveillance and monitoring due to this increased cancer risk.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 61.","responses":[{"text":"Melanoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barrett esophagus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Budd chiari syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoid tumor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22391,"text":"Upon abdominal examination of a patient, the doctor finds collaterals present as dilated subcutaneous veins extending from the umbilicus toward the rib margins. Sinusoidal dilation that occurs in portal hypertension is known as?","explanation":"**Caput medusae** is a distinctive clinical finding associated with portal hypertension. It is named after the mythological figure Medusa, whose hair was composed of snakes. In this condition, the dilated and tortuous veins resemble the appearance of snakes under the skin, particularly radiating outward from the umbilicus. \r\n\r\nPortal hypertension occurs when there is increased pressure within the portal venous system, often due to liver disease or obstruction of blood flow within the liver. This elevated pressure can lead to the development of collateral blood vessels, such as those seen in caput medusae, as the blood seeks alternative pathways to bypass the liver.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 517.","responses":[{"text":"Spider angiomas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Budd Chiari syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fetor hepaticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caput medusae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peliosis hepatis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22393,"text":"A patient presented to the emergency room with a perforated duodenal ulcer. Ultrasound shows that the perforation is present on the posterior wall of the first part of the duodenum. Which of the following arteries could be involved in this case?","explanation":"The **gastroduodenal artery** is a branch of the common hepatic artery, which, in turn, arises from the coeliac trunk. It supplies blood to various structures in the upper abdomen, including the stomach and the duodenum. The posterior wall of the first part of the duodenum, where the ulcer is located, can receive its blood supply from the gastroduodenal artery.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 312.","responses":[{"text":"Splenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroepiploic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroduodenal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior mesenteric","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22394,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is present on the brush border epithelium of the intestine that breaks down 1,6-glycosidic linkages?","explanation":"**Isomaltase** is a crucial enzyme involved in the digestion of complex carbohydrates, specifically those with 1,6-glycosidic linkages. It plays a vital role in breaking down isomaltose and dextrin into simpler sugars like glucose. This process is essential for the absorption of these sugars in the small intestine.","reference":"Oligo 1,6 Glucosidase - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/oligo-1-6-glucosidase#:~:text=Isomaltase%20is%20the%20only%20enzyme,digestion%20is%20summarized%20in%20Fig. Accessed 8 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Maltase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sucrase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucoamylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isomaltase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22396,"text":"A 42-year-old female underwent an ultrasound abdomen due to non-specific abdominal pain. Ultrasound shows a well-defined anechoic lesion in the liver with posterior acoustic enhancement. No evidence of echoes within the lesion. The given explanation best corresponds to which one of the following lesions?","explanation":"**Hepatic cysts** are fluid-filled sacs within the liver and are often benign. On ultrasound, they appear as well-defined, round or oval lesions with a fluid-filled center, resulting in anechoic (black) appearance. The posterior acoustic enhancement, where the sound waves pass easily through the cyst and create increased brightness on the far side, is a characteristic feature. Importantly, hepatic cysts typically do not show any internal echoes or solid components.","reference":"Alshaikhli A, Al-Hillan A. Liver Cystic Disease. [Updated 2023 Apr 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567739","responses":[{"text":"Hepatic hydatid cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic cyst","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic hemangioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic metastasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22397,"text":"A 13-year-old girl presented with severe weight loss, and recurrent episodes of diarrhea, containing blood and mucus from last year. There was also a history of lower abdominal pain as well. She has visited multiple hospitals and taken antibiotics but has not improved clinically. Her fecal calprotectin levels were highly raised. Her barium enema showed a string sign in the ileal region. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)** is a chronic inflammatory condition that includes two main types: Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis. In this case, the presence of bloody diarrhea, the string sign on barium enema (indicative of bowel strictures), and the highly elevated fecal calprotectin levels, which is a marker of intestinal inflammation, strongly suggest IBD as the most likely diagnosis.\r\n\r\nFurther evaluation and confirmation, such as endoscopy and biopsy, may be needed to differentiate between Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis.","reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2018: 279.","responses":[{"text":"Acute gastroenteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac Disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilic gastroenteritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22398,"text":"A 3-year-old child comes to you with complaints of recurrent diarrhea since 8 months of age. The stools are bulky and foul-smelling. He was started on a complementary diet at 6 months of age. The weight is 7 kg. His Stool DR shows numerous fat globules. What further investigation you will advise to confirm the diagnosis?","explanation":"The clinical presentation with these symptoms, along with numerous fat globules in the stool, raises suspicion of **celiac disease,** a condition characterized by gluten intolerance and malabsorption. **Tissue Transglutaminase IgA antibody and anti-endomysial IgA antibody** are specific diagnostic tests for celiac disease. However, it's important to check the total serum IgA levels as well, as IgA deficiency can be common in celiac disease, and it can affect the accuracy of these tests.","reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2018: 277.","responses":[{"text":"Stool culture and sensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue Transglutaminase IgA and serum IgA","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool for reducing substance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium meal and follow through","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue Transglutaminase IgG and Serum IgA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22399,"text":"A 5-year-old child presented with a history of abdominal distension for the last 2 weeks. He has a history of recurrent foul-smelling, bulky stools containing no blood or mucus. He was admitted to the hospital 2 times with the above-mentioned complaints, but not. improved. On examination, his weight was 11 Kg, height was 99 cm, edematous child with hypo and hyperpigmentation all over the body. There was no peri-orbital edema, heart sounds were audible. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The clinical features, such as abdominal distension, recurrent foul-smelling stools, failure to thrive (as evidenced by the child's low weight and height), and hypo and hyperpigmentation, are indicative of a malabsorption disorder. **Malabsorptive syndromes** result from the impaired absorption of nutrients from the gastrointestinal tract. In this case, the child's symptoms suggest a significant problem with nutrient absorption, likely affecting fat absorption since foul-smelling, bulky stools are characteristic of steatorrhea, which is the presence of excessive fat in the feces.","reference":"Azer SA, Sankararaman S. Steatorrhea. [Updated 2023 May 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541055/","responses":[{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorptive syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22419,"text":"A 19-year-old male with a broken ankle after a fall was given hydrocodone (opioid analgesic) for pain. The patient had nausea and vomited once, and was given ondansetron to treat his nausea. What is the mechanism of action of ondansetron?","explanation":"The 5-HT3 receptors are a subtype of serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine or 5-HT) receptors found in the central nervous system and the gastrointestinal tract. When serotonin binds to these receptors, it can trigger nausea and vomiting. **Ondansetron works by blocking these 5-HT3 receptors,** preventing serotonin from binding to them and thereby reducing the sensation of nausea and the reflex to vomit.\r\n\r\nThis mechanism of action makes ondansetron particularly effective in managing nausea and vomiting associated with chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and postoperative recovery, as well as in cases like the one described, where opioid analgesics are likely to induce nausea and vomiting as a side effect.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 546.","responses":[{"text":"H2 receptor inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 HT3-antagonist","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"D2 receptor antagonist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Substance P antagonist","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22420,"text":"Which H2 receptor blocker has the maximum inhibitory effect on microsomal cytochrome P-450?","explanation":"**Cimetidine** is an H2 receptor antagonist commonly used to reduce stomach acid production in conditions like peptic ulcers and gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). It not only acts on H2 receptors in the stomach to decrease acid secretion but also has some notable interactions with other drugs due to its ability to inhibit cytochrome P-450 enzymes in the liver.\r\n\r\nCimetidine can inhibit these enzymes, slowing down the metabolism of drugs that are substrates for cytochrome P-450. This inhibition can lead to increased levels of these drugs in the bloodstream, potentially causing adverse effects or drug interactions.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Famotidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nazatidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Roxatidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranitidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22421,"text":"Which of the following are the primary mechanisms by which prostaglandins promote ulcer healing?","explanation":"Prostaglandins stimulate the **production and secretion of mucus** from specialized cells in the stomach lining. This mucus forms a thick, protective layer that covers the inner surface of the stomach and duodenum. It is **rich in bicarbonate ions,** which help neutralize stomach acid, maintaining a less acidic environment at the mucosal surface. This buffered mucus layer acts as a physical barrier, preventing direct contact between gastric acid and the sensitive mucosa, thus reducing the risk of ulcer formation and promoting the healing of existing ulcers.","reference":"Konturek, S. J. “Prostaglandins in Pathophysiology of Peptic Ulcer Disease.” Digestive Diseases and Sciences, Nov. 1985, http://link.springer.com/10.1007/BF01309393.","responses":[{"text":"Increase bicarbonate secretion in gastric juice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preventing pathogenic bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of gastric secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased turnover of gastric mucosal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Augmentation of bicarbonate buffered mucus layer covering gastro-duodenal mucosa","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22506,"text":"A 45-year-old male is presented complaining of vomiting off/on for one month. CT scan abdomen shows a cystic lesion in the tail of the pancreas compressing the stomach. Which of the following findings is indicative of the benign nature of the disease?","explanation":"In this case, the patient presents with a cystic lesion in the tail of the pancreas that is compressing the stomach. The differential diagnosis includes pseudocysts and cystic neoplasms. \r\n\r\nOne of the key differentiating factors is the amylase level in the cystic fluid. **A high amylase level (\u003e3000 IU/L) in the cystic fluid is indicative of a pseudocyst**, which is a collection of amylase-rich fluid enclosed in a well-defined wall of fibrous or granulation tissue. Pseudocysts typically arise following an attack of mild acute pancreatitis and are considered benign in nature.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, cystic neoplasms may have lower amylase levels and may show elevated levels of carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA).","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1228.","responses":[{"text":"Cystic fluid amylase level of more than 3000 IU/L","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complex cystic lesion on endoscopic ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CEA level of 500mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"History of mild upper quadrant pain at least a month ago","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of atypical cells in cystic fluid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22507,"text":"A 30-year-old male presents in the emergency department with a history of severe abdominal pain. His laboratory investigation shows amylase of 3000IU/L. Which of the following prognostic factors is unfavorable for this patient?","explanation":"In acute pancreatitis, several prognostic factors are used to assess the severity of the disease and predict outcomes. These factors include the Ranson score, transient organ failure, CT severity index, and C-reactive protein level.\r\n\r\nThe Ranson score is a widely used tool to predict the severity of acute pancreatitis. A score of 3 or more indicates a higher risk of complications and a poorer prognosis.\r\n\r\nTransient organ failure, such as respiratory distress or renal dysfunction, is also associated with a worse outcome.\r\n\r\nHowever, **multiple organ failure** is the most unfavorable prognostic factor among these options. It signifies the involvement of multiple organ systems and is associated with a significantly increased risk of mortality in acute pancreatitis.","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1223.","responses":[{"text":"C-reactive protein of 100mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT severity index of 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranson score of 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple organ failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transient organ failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22508,"text":"A 38-year-old female presents in the emergency department with a history of severe pain in the epigastric region and multiple episodes of vomiting for one day and gets admitted as a case of acute pancreatitis. CT scan abdomen shows a CTSI of 8/10. After 2 days of conservative management, the pain has decreased but she is not tolerating it orally.  which of the following routes is preferred for nutritional support?","explanation":"In acute pancreatitis, the gastrointestinal tract is typically functional, but oral feeding can exacerbate symptoms due to the release of digestive enzymes. Therefore, early enteral nutrition is recommended to maintain gut function, prevent gut barrier dysfunction, and reduce the risk of infection.\r\n\r\n**Nasojejunal feeding** allows for the delivery of nutrients beyond the stomach, avoiding stimulation of pancreatic enzyme secretion. This approach is associated with a lower risk of complications compared to parenteral nutrition, which should be reserved for cases where enteral nutrition is not feasible.\r\n\r\nFeeding gastrostomy may also be considered but is generally used when nasojejunal feeding is not possible or contraindicated.\r\n\r\nTotal parenteral nutrition should be reserved for situations where enteral nutrition is not an option, as it carries a higher risk of complications.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Surgery lecture ''Acute pancreatitis'' Management, slide 14.","responses":[{"text":"Total parenteral nutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Feeding gastrostomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral feeding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Partial parenteral nutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasojejunal feeding","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22509,"text":"A 30-year-old female experiences an acute episode of right hypochondriac pain following a meal. She has had a similar episode in the past that was managed conservatively. On examination, she holds her breath on deep palpation of the right hypochondrium. On ultrasound, there are gallstones with pericholecystic fluid present. what is the best initial step in management?","explanation":"The patient's presentation is suggestive of acute cholecystitis, which is inflammation of the gallbladder often caused by gallstones. In such cases, the initial approach is conservative management, which includes **fasting (NPO)** to allow the gallbladder to rest and administering **IV antibiotics** to treat any associated infection. **Analgesics** can help alleviate pain.\r\n\r\nEmergent surgical intervention may be required in cases of complicated or severe cholecystitis, but it's not the best initial step. CT scan and ERCP are not typically the first-line diagnostic or management options for acute cholecystitis.\r\n\r\nUltrasound-guided cholecystostomy tube placement may be considered in selected cases but is generally reserved for patients who are not surgical candidates or in whom surgery is contraindicated.","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1200.","responses":[{"text":"ERCP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keep the patient NPO, start IV antibiotics and analgesic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Emergent surgical intervention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Place ultrasound guided cholecystostomy tube","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22510,"text":"A 35-year-old male presents in emergency, with severe abdominal pain since one day. He has a history of pulmonary tuberculosis one year back. On examination, his pulse is 120 beats/minute. Abdomen is tense and tender. There is free year under diaphragm in erect X-ray. What is the next best step in the management of this patient?","explanation":"The presentation of severe abdominal pain, a tense and tender abdomen, and the presence of free air under the diaphragm in an erect X-ray strongly suggests the possibility of a perforated viscus, such as a perforated peptic ulcer, diverticulitis, or in this case, gastrointestinal tuberculosis. Given the patient's history of pulmonary tuberculosis, it is important to consider the possibility of tuberculosis involving the gastrointestinal tract, which can lead to complications like bowel perforation.\r\n\r\nAn **exploratory laparotomy** is a surgical procedure that allows direct visualization of the abdominal contents, assessment of the extent of damage, and appropriate intervention. It is crucial to identify the source of the perforation, assess the extent of abdominal involvement, and manage any associated complications promptly.","reference":"D'24 lecture slides, \"TB Abdomen\", slide 28.\r\n\r\nJones MW, Kashyap S, Zabbo CP. Bowel Perforation. [Updated 2023 Apr 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537224/","responses":[{"text":"Ultrasound guided pigtail insertion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conservative management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Start anti-tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exploratory laparotomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colonoscopy and biopsy of terminal ileum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22511,"text":"A 45-year-old male patient with a history of hyperlipidemia and hypertension presents to clinic for a dietary consultation. He is concerned about his risk for cardiovascular disease and wants to improve his health. You explain the importance of the omega-3 and of omega-6 PUFAs in managing inflammation and improving cardiovascular health. Which mechanism describes how increasing dietary consumption omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs) in comparison to omega-6 PUFA can contribute to reducing inflammation and the risk of cardiovascular disease?","explanation":"**Omega-3 PUFAS compete with the enzymes that convert arachidonic acid into eicosanoids (PG, TX, LTs)**, which is a key mechanism in how increasing dietary consumption of omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs) can contribute to reducing inflammation and the risk of cardiovascular disease. Omega-3 PUFAs, such as eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), are incorporated into cell membranes. These fatty acids are substrates for the same enzymes (cyclooxygenase and lipoxygenase) that convert omega-6 PUFA (arachidonic acid) into pro-inflammatory eicosanoids like prostaglandins (PG), thromboxanes (TX), and leukotrienes (LTs). However, the eicosanoids produced from omega-3 PUFAs are generally less inflammatory or even anti-inflammatory compared to those derived from arachidonic acid. By competing for these enzymes, omega-3 PUFAs can decrease the production of pro-inflammatory eicosanoids from arachidonic acid, thereby reducing inflammation and potentially lowering the risk of chronic diseases, including cardiovascular diseases.","reference":"Surette ME. The science behind dietary omega-3 fatty acids. Canadian Medical Association Journal. Published January 15, 2008. Accessed January 8, 2024. http://www.cmaj.ca/cgi/doi/10.1503/cmaj.071356","responses":[{"text":"Omega-3 PUFAs promote the synthesis of arachidonic acid, inhibiting inflammatory eicosanoid production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omega-3 PUFAs inhibit the production of arachidonic acid, a precursor to inflammatory eicosanoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omega-3 PUFAS compete with the enzymes that convert arachidonic acid into eicosanoids (PG, TX, LTs)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omega-3 PUFAs enhance the ability of platelets to release TXA2, reducing the risk of coagulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omega-3 PUFAS compete with the inflammatory properties imparted by omega-6 PUFAs","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

